time required: 30 minutes
---

Adjust racks to top and middle positions and preheat #oven{} to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @potatoes{12%ounce} into 1⁄2-inch-thick wedges. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens; mince whites. Cut @broccoli{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary.

Toss potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of @cooking oil{drizzle}, @fry seasoning{1%tablespoon}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack until browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

While potatoes roast, in a #large bowl{}, combine @ground beef{10%ounce}, scallion whites, @panko breadcrumbs{1/2%cup}, @beef stock concentrate{1}, 1 TBSP water, 1⁄2 tsp salt, and pepper (2 TBSP water and 1 tsp salt for 4 servings).

Form beef mixture into two 1-inch-tall loaves (four loaves for 4). Place on one side of a second baking sheet.

> TIP: If you added any other items to your meal (apps, sides, and/or dessert), you can get started on them now!

Toss broccoli on opposite side of sheet from meatloaves with a drizzle of oil, salt, and pepper. Top broccoli with @cheddar cheese{1/2%cup}.

Roast on middle rack until broccoli is tender and meatloaves are cooked through, ~{15-20%minutes} (if broccoli finishes first, carefully remove from sheet and continue roasting meatloaves).

> TIP: If you prefer cheesy potatoes, skip adding cheese to broccoli and instead remove potatoes from oven after 20-22 minutes; top with cheddar, then return sheet to top rack and roast until cheese melts, 2-3 minutes more.

Meanwhile, in a #small pot{} over medium heat, combine @ketchup{1}, @BBQ sauce{4%tablespoon}, @brown sugar{1%tablespoon}, and 2 TBSP water (4 TBSP for 4 servings). Cook, stirring occasionally, until sauce has thickened and is warmed through, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Transfer meatloaves to a #cutting board{}. Slice crosswise.

Serve potatoes, meatloaves, broccoli, BBQ sauce, @sour cream{3%tablespoon}, and scallion greens family style for everyone to build their own plate. (Don't forget to serve with any extra items you may have ordered to build out your meal!)

> Ground Meat is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.